 LINK Command-Line Syntax 

     LINK objfiles [,exefile,mapfile,libraries,deffile] [;]

     <objfiles>     Object files to be linked. Separate multiple file
                    names by plus (+) or space characters. At least one
                    name must be entered. Library files can also be
                    entered. A special syntax allows you to define
                    overlays.
                    See: Entering Library Files as Object Files
                         Specifying Overlays

     <exefile>      Output file. LINK produces either an executable
                    file or a dynamic-link library.

     <mapfile>      Listing of modules in <exefile>. Use the /M option
                    to include public symbols in this file. Enter NUL
                    if you do not want a map file.
                    See: Include Public Symbols (/M)

     <libraries>    Standard or import (not dynamic-link) libraries to
                    be used in resolving external references. Separate
                    multiple file names by plus (+) or space
                    characters. Some libraries are searched by default.
                    You can also specify a path to a directory--LINK
                    searches all libraries in this directory.
                    See: Linking with an Import Library
                         Default Libraries
                         Specifying Library Directories

     <deffile>      Module-definition file (for OS/2 and Windows
                    linking only).
                    See: Module-Definition Files

     Options modify LINK's actions. Options can appear anywhere on the
     command line before the semicolon (except as noted).
     See: LINK Options
          Using LINK Options

     Special Features

        . LINK creates the executable file and map file in the current
          directory unless you enter an explicit path.

        . LINK looks in several locations for object, library, and
          module-definition files.
          See: Where LINK Looks for Files

        . If you enter a file name without an extension, LINK adds a
          default extension that depends on the type of file expected.
          See: File-Name-Extension Defaults

        . If you leave a field blank (but define the field with a
          comma), LINK uses a default for the field. If you end the
          LINK command with a semicolon (;), LINK uses defaults for all
          remaining fields.
          See: File-Name Defaults

        . If you do not give all file names or do not end the command
          line with a semicolon, LINK prompts you for the omitted
          files.
          See: LINK Prompts
